ApplicationContext:

Definition: ApplicationContext is a more advanced container compared to BeanFactory.
Role: It includes everything BeanFactory does, plus more features like:

Internationalization (i18n)
Event propagation
Application-layer specific contexts (e.g., WebApplicationContext)
Bean auto-wiring

Usage: It is the standard container in most Spring applications.
Example:

ApplicationContext context = new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");
UserService userService = context.getBean(UserService.class);

Note: ApplicationContext eagerly creates all singleton beans at startup.

Feature	                    BeanFactory	                         ApplicationContext

Definition	                Basic IoC container	                 Advanced IoC container (extends BeanFactory)
Initialization	            Lazy (beans created when requested)	 Eager (singleton beans created at startup)
Features	                Only basic DI	                     DI + event handling, i18n, AOP, etc.
Use Case	                Lightweight, memory-sensitive apps	 Standard for most Spring applications
Common Usage	            Rarely used directly in modern apps	 Used in almost all Spring projects